  "description": "<p>In this post I briefly discuss some recent stunning progress on robust bandits (for more background on bandits see these two posts, part 1 and part 2, in particular what is described below gives a solution to Open Problem 3 &#8230; <a href=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/2019/06/10/amazing-progress-in-adversarially-robust-stochastic-multi-armed-bandits/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&#8594;</span></a></p>\n",
  "content:encoded": "<p>In this post I briefly discuss some recent stunning progress on robust bandits (for more background on bandits see these two posts, <a href=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/2016/05/11/bandit-theory-part-i/\" class=\"liinternal\">part 1</a> and <a href=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/2016/05/13/bandit-theory-part-ii/\" class=\"liinternal\">part 2</a>, in particular what is described below gives a solution to Open Problem 3 at the end of part 2).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Stochastic bandit and adversarial examples</strong></p>\n<p>In multi-armed bandit problems the gold standard property, going back to <a href=\"https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/82425825.pdf\" class=\"lipdf\">a seminal paper</a> of Lai and Robbins in 1985 is to have a regret upper bounded by:</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 50px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> (1) </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-2ac69fee3f1e4890b09202da232941f6_l3.png\" height=\"50\" width=\"91\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#98;&#101;&#103;&#105;&#110;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125; &#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#40;&#84;&#41;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44;&#46; &#92;&#101;&#110;&#100;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>Let me unpack this a bit: this is for the scenario where the reward process for each action is simply an i.i.d. sequence from some fixed distribution, <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-9af0b76a90462b68c1d83fca9cc6604d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#105;&#94;&#42;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"13\" width=\"12\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> is the index of the (unique) best action, and <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-9ca6025283881ee4c29a1f9f236d72ba_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"15\" width=\"20\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px;\"/> is the gap between the mean value of the best action and the one of <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-8511b1f6cf9db17d46ddabb67bac99f5_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#105;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"6\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/>. Such guarantee is extremely strong, as in particular it means that actions whose average performance is a constant away from the optimal arm are very rarely played (only of order <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-b7ebb3614adc5ab9694e195d68bdbd06_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#40;&#84;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"49\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/>). On the other hand, the price to pay for such an aggressive behavior (by this I mean focusing on good actions very quickly) is that all the classical algorithms attaining the above bound are extremely sensitive to <em>adversarial examples</em>: that is if there is some deviation from the i.i.d. assumption (even very brief in time), the algorithms can suddenly suffer linear in <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-58f18d11e5ffdd11dd9095c427922c8b_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#84;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"13\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> regret.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Adversarial bandit</strong></p>\n<p>Of course there is an entirely different line of works, on <em>adversarial multi-armed bandits</em>, where the whole point is to prove regret guarantee for <em>any</em> reward process. In this case the best one can hope for is a regret of order <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-13ba497e024059e3674272b6a0e11809_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"44\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px;\"/>. The classical algorithm in this model, Exp3, attains a regret of order <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-fc756065e4451f8bccc02a40b732c969_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#40;&#75;&#41;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"22\" width=\"103\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/>. In joint work with Jean-Yves Audibert we showed <a href=\"http://sbubeck.com/COLT09_AB.pdf\" class=\"lipdf\">back in 2009</a> that the following strategy, which we called PolyINF, attains the optimal <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-3cf8321c07956bc2bd76714eabd30a0a_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#84;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"44\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px;\"/>: view Exp3 as Mirror Descent with the (negative) entropy as a regularizer, and now replace the entropy by a simple rational function namely <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-ac7b6228954b4b6f9ceee99faf3d7776_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#45;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#94;&#112;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"24\" width=\"77\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/> with <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-de24a5fa6badcd9e8c80a7d72640dcc6_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#112;&#32;&#92;&#105;&#110;&#32;&#40;&#48;&#44;&#49;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"70\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> (this mirror descent view was actually derived in <a href=\"https://pubsonline.informs.org/doi/10.1287/moor.2013.0598\" class=\"liinternal\">a later paper</a> with Gabor Lugosi). The proof becomes one line (given the appropriate knowledge of mirror descent and estimation in bandit games): the radius part of the bound is of the form <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-a3d6ffad60b5151ac3866f9fa9213b65_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#94;&#112;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#75;&#94;&#123;&#112;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"27\" width=\"120\" style=\"vertical-align: -9px;\"/>, while the variance is of the form (since the inverse of the Hessian of the mirror map is a diagonal matrix with entries <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-0b3188b0bc4d641381b7ba4be936c230_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#120;&#95;&#105;&#94;&#123;&#50;&#45;&#112;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"23\" width=\"35\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/>):</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 46px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-5356f94049f314f34752afbac2277f16_l3.png\" height=\"46\" width=\"177\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#91; &#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#94;&#123;&#50;&#45;&#112;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#32;&#75;&#94;&#123;&#49;&#45;&#112;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44;&#46; &#92;&#93;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>Thus optimizing over <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-86bde2afc6c0858d01ac505267801f02_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"9\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> yields <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-13ba497e024059e3674272b6a0e11809_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"44\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px;\"/> for any <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-de24a5fa6badcd9e8c80a7d72640dcc6_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#112;&#32;&#92;&#105;&#110;&#32;&#40;&#48;&#44;&#49;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"70\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/>. Interestingly, the best numerical constant in the bound is obtained for <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-d9aaa949f328021d5d7cbd31573c7a0e_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#112;&#61;&#49;&#47;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"60\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Best of both worlds</strong></p>\n<p>This was the state of affairs back in 2011, when with Alex Slivkins we started working on a <em>best of both worlds</em> type algorithm (which in today&#8217;s language is exactly a stochastic MAB robust to adversarial examples): namely one that gets the <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-b7ebb3614adc5ab9694e195d68bdbd06_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#40;&#84;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"49\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> guarantee (in fact <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-00cc550d710d51cc64227da3b639018e_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#94;&#50;&#40;&#84;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"20\" width=\"56\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> in <a href=\"http://sbubeck.com/COLT12_BS.pdf\" class=\"lipdf\">our original paper</a>) if the environment is the nice i.i.d. one, and also <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-13ba497e024059e3674272b6a0e11809_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"44\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px;\"/> (in fact <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-4d85e820be8841c565042231480be3ac_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#94;&#51;&#40;&#84;&#41;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"33\" width=\"107\" style=\"vertical-align: -10px;\"/>) in the worst case. This original best of both worlds algorithm was of the following form: be aggressive as if it was a stochastic environment, but still sample sufficiently often the bad actions to make sure there isn&#8217;t an adversary trying to hide some non-stochastic behavior on these seemingly bad performing actions. Of course the whole difficulty was to show that it is possible to implement such a defense without hurting the stochastic performance too much (remember that bad actions can only be sampled of order <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-b7ebb3614adc5ab9694e195d68bdbd06_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#108;&#111;&#103;&#40;&#84;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"49\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> times!). Since this COLT 2012 paper there has been many improvements to the original strategy, as well as many variants/refinements (one such variant worth mentioning are the works trying to do a smooth transition between the stochastic and adversarial models, see e.g. <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.09353\" class=\"liinternal\">here</a> and <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1902.08647\" class=\"liinternal\">here</a>).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>A stunning twist</strong></p>\n<p>The amazing development that I want to talk about in this post is the following: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1807.07623\" class=\"liinternal\">about a year ago</a> Julian Zimmert and Yevgeny Seldin proved that the 2009 PolyINF (crucially with <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-d9aaa949f328021d5d7cbd31573c7a0e_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#112;&#61;&#49;&#47;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"60\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/>) strategy actually gets the 2012 best of both worlds bound! This is truly surprising, as in principle mirror descent does not &#8220;know&#8221; anything about stochastic environments, it does not make any sophisticated concentration reasoning (say as in Lai and Robbins), yet it seems to automatically and optimally pick up on the regularity in the data. This is really amazing to me, and of course also a total surprise that the polynomial regularizer has such strong adaptivity property, while it was merely introduced to remove a benign log term.</p>\n<p>The crucial observation of Zimmert and Seldin is that a a certain <em>self-bounding</em> property of the regret implies (in a one-line calculation) the best of both worlds result:</p>\n<blockquote><p><strong>Lemma 1:</strong> Consider a strategy whose regret with respect to the optimal action <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-9af0b76a90462b68c1d83fca9cc6604d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#105;&#94;&#42;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"13\" width=\"12\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> is upper bounded by</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 56px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> (2) </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-58ac492ce88752df4dbc5bccc5f7c9ff_l3.png\" height=\"56\" width=\"129\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#98;&#101;&#103;&#105;&#110;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125; &#67;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44;&#46; &#92;&#101;&#110;&#100;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>(Recall that for multi-armed bandit one selects a probability distribution <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-ae5b82123ba785d8c8153a037675bc56_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#120;&#95;&#116;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"11\" width=\"15\" style=\"vertical-align: -3px;\"/> over the actions, so <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-65be0e3045aefe9ef0dd0bd9531c0572_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"14\" width=\"24\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/> denote here the probability of playing action <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-8511b1f6cf9db17d46ddabb67bac99f5_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#105;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"6\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> at time <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-6b97bb0f65c75b6cc0fba1868749478d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#116;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"6\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/>.) Then one has that the regret is in fact bounded by <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-6dc96815294ab91f00db7fc32adcc459_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#50;&#32;&#67;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#75;&#32;&#84;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"68\" style=\"vertical-align: -2px;\"/> (this follows trivially by Jensen on the <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-8511b1f6cf9db17d46ddabb67bac99f5_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#105;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"6\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> sum), and moreover if the environment is stochastic one has that the regret is in fact bounded by <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-e4b609168e948e0de36c4f357b700408_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#67;&#94;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"15\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> times <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-5048b7c449e02713d954071d1a80df0f_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#40;&#49;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/>.</p></blockquote>\n<p><em>Proof:</em> Assuming that the environment is stochastic we can write the regret as <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-1e451f2e1cd6b24d6f4ceb19592378a8_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"21\" width=\"80\" style=\"vertical-align: -8px;\"/>, so by assumption and using that <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-37d8baadc3f1897c077c0f1bc6da832f_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#67;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#50;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#102;&#116;&#40;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#67;&#94;&#50;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#114;&#105;&#103;&#104;&#116;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"33\" width=\"205\" style=\"vertical-align: -12px;\"/> one has:</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 52px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-19259c6dbd863aa77917fbddee306ca7_l3.png\" height=\"52\" width=\"295\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#91; &#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#50;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#102;&#116;&#40;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#67;&#94;&#50;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#114;&#105;&#103;&#104;&#116;&#41;&#32;&#92;&#44;&#44; &#92;&#93;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>which means that the left hand side is smaller than <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-3a170cbde4999b8a9aaab3ebc7698acb_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#67;&#94;&#50;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#32;&#92;&#68;&#101;&#108;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#105;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"26\" width=\"82\" style=\"vertical-align: -8px;\"/> which is indeed smaller than <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-e4b609168e948e0de36c4f357b700408_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#67;&#94;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"15\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> times <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-5048b7c449e02713d954071d1a80df0f_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#40;&#49;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Yet another one-line proof (okay, maybe 5 lines)</strong></p>\n<p>Zimmert and Seldin proved that PolyINF with <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-d9aaa949f328021d5d7cbd31573c7a0e_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#112;&#61;&#49;&#47;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"60\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/> actually satisfies the self-bounding property of Lemma 1 (and thus obtains the best of both worlds guarantee). In <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1901.08779\" class=\"liinternal\">another recent paper</a> by Zimmert, in joint work with Haipeng Luo and Chen-Yu Wei, they simplify the analysis by using a very mild variation of the PolyINF regularizer, namely <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-83b29164db23b237061cd205df4a585d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#45;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#40;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"24\" width=\"183\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/>. In my view it&#8217;s the proof from the book for the best of both worlds result (or very close to it)! Here it is:</p>\n<blockquote><p><strong>Lemma 2:</strong> Equation <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-8a996880dc323ee4b8cf323009c02635_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#40;&#50;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> with <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-ae0daffd6d9302e8baf8d6432a69c5ca_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#67;&#61;&#49;&#48;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"13\" width=\"56\" style=\"vertical-align: -1px;\"/> is an upper bound on the regret of mirror descent with learning <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-27f9c61a5d83fe6d2fca62581c4d1b6f_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"27\" width=\"57\" style=\"vertical-align: -11px;\"/>, mirror map <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-e28928d4c9de69492e5f786c52e80f3e_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#80;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#41;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#40;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#125;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"24\" width=\"245\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/>, and standard multi-armed bandit loss estimator.</p></blockquote>\n<p><em>Proof:</em> The classical mirror descent analysis from any good book will tell you that the regret is controlled by (for <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-f1d27d479269ff49c66d302354f84569_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#80;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#41;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#95;&#105;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"24\" width=\"144\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/> and with the convention <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-db68debdd0cb300a9b79aed311c05d28_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#48;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#105;&#110;&#102;&#116;&#121;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"15\" width=\"71\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/>):</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 54px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> (3) </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-d3de9d0c55a8d8aca491d928972530ed_l3.png\" height=\"54\" width=\"437\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#98;&#101;&#103;&#105;&#110;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125; &#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#102;&#116;&#40;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#45;&#49;&#125;&#125;&#92;&#114;&#105;&#103;&#104;&#116;&#41;&#32;&#40;&#92;&#80;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#94;&#42;&#41;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#92;&#80;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#95;&#116;&#41;&#41;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;''&#40;&#120;&#95;&#116;&#41;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44;&#46; &#92;&#101;&#110;&#100;&#123;&#101;&#113;&#117;&#97;&#116;&#105;&#111;&#110;&#42;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>We now consider those terms for the specific <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-8581dbc45f448345dcc6bd9caed502e9_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#80;&#104;&#105;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"14\" width=\"12\" style=\"vertical-align: -1px;\"/> and <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-f489909a6f16a3b5a6ee23901d48d9b6_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"12\" width=\"14\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> suggested in the lemma. First notice that <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-7f8f2af48129af0fd204515d14d0f6f5_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;&#125;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#45;&#49;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#101;&#116;&#97;&#95;&#116;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"25\" width=\"105\" style=\"vertical-align: -9px;\"/>. Moreover <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-e59356dfe693c9414f1e407c034a4a4d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#94;&#42;&#95;&#105;&#41;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#49;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"19\" width=\"88\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/> (since <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-1b92fd5178a7e53e81d04a267f41c9d8_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#120;&#94;&#42;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"13\" width=\"16\" style=\"vertical-align: 0px;\"/> is integral) so that <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-a13944e230b8362a3c996cdb9d42f634_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#94;&#42;&#95;&#105;&#41;&#32;&#45;&#32;&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;&#40;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#41;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#109;&#105;&#110;&#40;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#44;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"22\" width=\"298\" style=\"vertical-align: -7px;\"/>. In other words the first term in <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-c9264e4ae133cc333e4e98394c7e0656_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#40;&#51;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> is upper bounded by</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 57px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-c048790fe35996074b87ea676060d91d_l3.png\" height=\"57\" width=\"350\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#91; &#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#92;&#109;&#105;&#110;&#40;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#44;&#32;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#41;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#50;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44; &#92;&#93;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>where the inequality simply comes from <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-01c4dcfc661631d69e71024a0340222d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"33\" width=\"307\" style=\"vertical-align: -13px;\"/>.</p>\n<p>Next note that <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-83fb6f1ccbc0d202e6020dc0884a140f_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#92;&#112;&#104;&#105;''&#40;&#115;&#41;&#32;&#61;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#52;&#125;&#32;&#40;&#115;&#94;&#123;&#45;&#51;&#47;&#50;&#125;&#32;&#43;&#32;&#40;&#49;&#45;&#115;&#41;&#94;&#123;&#45;&#51;&#47;&#50;&#125;&#41;&#32;&#92;&#103;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#49;&#125;&#123;&#52;&#32;&#92;&#109;&#105;&#110;&#40;&#115;&#44;&#49;&#45;&#115;&#41;&#94;&#123;&#51;&#47;&#50;&#125;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"28\" width=\"358\" style=\"vertical-align: -11px;\"/>, so that the second term in <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-c9264e4ae133cc333e4e98394c7e0656_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#40;&#51;&#41;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"21\" style=\"vertical-align: -4px;\"/> is upper bounded by</p>\n<p class=\"ql-center-displayed-equation\" style=\"line-height: 57px;\"><span class=\"ql-right-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><span class=\"ql-left-eqno\"> &nbsp; </span><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-98a3e5f8a743148f5f6919b1dd53a8b9_l3.png\" height=\"57\" width=\"442\" class=\"ql-img-displayed-equation \" alt=\"&#92;&#91; &#52;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#75;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#109;&#105;&#110;&#40;&#49;&#44;&#32;&#40;&#49;&#45;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#41;&#47;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#41;&#94;&#123;&#51;&#47;&#50;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#108;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#56;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#116;&#61;&#49;&#125;&#94;&#84;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#117;&#109;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#32;&#92;&#110;&#101;&#113;&#32;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#115;&#113;&#114;&#116;&#123;&#92;&#102;&#114;&#97;&#99;&#123;&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#44;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#123;&#116;&#125;&#125;&#32;&#92;&#44; &#92;&#93;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\"/></p>\n<p>where the inequality follows trivially by considering the two cases whether <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-0bcf369611e215890249a1b1bb94089d_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#120;&#95;&#123;&#105;&#94;&#42;&#44;&#116;&#125;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"14\" width=\"31\" style=\"vertical-align: -6px;\"/> is smaller or larger than <img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://blogs.princeton.edu/imabandit/wp-content/ql-cache/quicklatex.com-1c652ece8cc629e4e659c41eeed4d410_l3.png\" class=\"ql-img-inline-formula \" alt=\"&#49;&#47;&#50;\" title=\"Rendered by QuickLaTeX.com\" height=\"18\" width=\"25\" style=\"vertical-align: -5px;\"/>.</p>\n",
